              <span id="reviewTextContainer187546620" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer247502091071311211">While the connections between the Paradise novels and the Circle trilogy cause me some confusion, I am very intrigued by the worlds that are portrayed in them and how they are connected to one another. As for Showdown in particular, I didn&apos;t like it as much as I thought I would. I enjoy Ted Dekker because of his creativity and originality, and these qualities usually draw me into his books. But Showdown&apos;s originality and creativity came off as a little too odd for me in this particular novel. I </span>
  <span id="freeText247502091071311211" style="display:none">While the connections between the Paradise novels and the Circle trilogy cause me some confusion, I am very intrigued by the worlds that are portrayed in them and how they are connected to one another. As for Showdown in particular, I didn't like it as much as I thought I would. I enjoy Ted Dekker because of his creativity and originality, and these qualities usually draw me into his books. But Showdown's originality and creativity came off as a little too odd for me in this particular novel. I liked the portrayal of Christ's sacrifice and the power of true, self-sacrificing love, but all of the details surrounding it seemed like he was trying a little to hard to portray the evil. I like the idea and the goal, but I don't think Dekker quite achieved that goal. </span>
